JS Constant

- The const keyword was introduced in ES6 (2015)
- Variables defined with const cannot be Redeclared
- Variables defined with const cannot be Reassigned

        const PI = 3.141592653589793;
        PI = 3.14;      // This will give an error
        PI = PI + 10;   // This will also give an error

- Variables defined with const have Block Scope
- âš ï¸ JavaScript const variables must be assigned a value when they are declared:

        const PI;   âŒ
        PI = 3.14159265359; 

        const PI = 3.14159265359; âœ…

WHEN TO USE JAVASCRIPT CONST?
- Always declare a variable with const when you know that the value should not be changed.
- Use const when you declare:
    A new Array
    A new Object
    A new Function
    A new RegExp

#) Constant Objects and Arrays:
    - ğŸš¨ The keyword const is a little misleading. IT DOES NOT DEFINE A CONSTANT VALUE. IT DEFINES A
        CONSTANT REFERENCE TO A VALUE.
    - Because of this you can NOT:
        -> Reassign a constant value
        -> Reassign a constant array
        -> Reassign a constant object
        But you CAN:
        -> Change the elements of constant array
        -> Change the properties of constant object

    (1) Constant Arrays: 
        - You can change the elements of a constant array and add new element âœ…:
           
            eg,
                const cars = ["Saab", "Volvo", "BMW"];

                // You can change an element:
                cars[0] = "Toyota";

                // You can add an element:
                cars.push("Audi");
        
        - But you can NOT reassign the array âŒ:
            
            eg, const cars = ["Saab", "Volvo", "BMW"];

                cars = ["Toyota", "Volvo", "Audi"];    // ERROR
    
    (2) Constant Objects: 
        - You can change the properties of a constant object and add new property âœ…:
            
            eg, 
                const car = {type:"Fiat", model:"500", color:"white"};

                // You can change a property:
                car.color = "red";

                // You can add a property:
                car.owner = "Johnson";
        
        - But you can NOT reassign the object âŒ:

            eg, const car = {type:"Fiat", model:"500", color:"white"};

                car = {type:"Volvo", model:"EX60", color:"red"}    // ERROR


#) const is Block Scope:
    - Declaring a variable with const is similar to let when it comes to Block Scope.
    - The x declared in the block, in this example, is not the same as the x declared
        outside the block:

            const x = 10;
            // Here x is 10

            {
            const x = 2;
            // Here x is 2
            }

            // Here x is 10

ğŸš¦ difference between var, let and const:

            Scope	Redeclare	Reassign	Hoisted	    Binds this
----------------------------------------------------------------------
var	        No	    Yes	        Yes	        Yes	        Yes
let	        Yes	    No	        Yes	        No	        No
const	    Yes	    No	        No	        No	        No

_________________________________________________________________________________________________________

ABSTRACT:

âœ… What is Good?
ğŸ‘‰ let and const can not be redeclared in the same scope.
ğŸ‘‰ let can be reassigned but const can not be reassigned in the same scope.
ğŸ‘‰ let and const have block scope.
ğŸ‘‰ let and const must be declared before use.
ğŸ‘‰ let and const does not bind to this.
ğŸ‘‰ let and const are not hoisted.

âŒ What is Not Good?
ğŸ‘‰ var does not have to be declared.
ğŸ‘‰ var is hoisted.
ğŸ‘‰ var binds to this.